You may have "fair use", "fair dealing", or similar rights for the software
under the law that applies to you. These terms do not limit them.

## Permitted Purposes

There are exactly two permitted purposes: Small Team Use and Non-Production Use.
Use that is not for a permitted purpose is not licensed under these terms and
needs a separate commercial license from the licensor.

## Small Team Use

Use of the software for the benefit of your company is use for a permitted
purpose if your company has fewer than 10 total individuals working as employees
and independent contractors. Ten or more, and this permitted purpose does not
cover you.

Count as follows.

1. **Count the whole company.** Your company includes every organization that
   has control over, is under the control of, or is under common control with
   the organization you work for. Count all of them together as one.
2. **Count people, not roles or hours.** Count each individual once, whether
   they work full-time or part-time, and whether or not they ever touch the
   software.
3. **Count at the time you use.** Apply the test at the time of the use in
   question.
4. **Count the individuals your company engages directly.** Individuals who work
   for an unaffiliated organization that your company engages at arm's length as
   a vendor — an outside law, accounting, or agency firm, for example — do not
   count, unless your company also engages them directly as employees or
   independent contractors.
5. **Substance, not form.** You may not split entities, restructure, or route
   people through intermediaries in order to appear to be under the limit. If
   the practical effect of an arrangement is that 10 or more individuals work
   for one business, the limit is not met.

If you do not use the software for the benefit of any company — you use it only
for yourself, for example — the size limit does not restrict you. If you are a
sole proprietor, count yourself.

If your company reaches 10 or more individuals, you have 30 days from the day it
does to obtain a commercial license or to stop using the software for anything
this permitted purpose no longer covers. Non-Production Use stays available to
you either way. This 30-day window is separate from the notice-and-cure period
in Violations.

This size limit does not expire. It does not lapse, relax, or convert into any
other license after any period of time.

## Non-Production Use

Non-production use of the software is a permitted purpose for anyone, whatever
the size of your company. This is deliberate: you should be able to try the
software, build against it, and study it before you owe anything.

Non-production use means:

- evaluating the software;
- developing, building, and testing the software, or software that works with
  it;
- non-commercial research or education.

Use is production use — and so needs Small Team Use or a commercial license —
when the software is relied on to carry on the actual work of a company or of
its customers, rather than to evaluate, develop, test, research, or teach.

Non-production use is still subject to Limitations.

## Commercial License

If your company has 10 or more individuals, or you want to do something these
terms do not permit — making the software available to others as a hosted or
managed service, for example — you need a separate written commercial license
from the licensor.

Contact support@exponential.at.

Nothing in these terms obliges the licensor to grant one, or to grant one on any
particular terms.

## Limitations

These limitations apply to every license granted by these terms, for every
permitted purpose, at every company size, and whether or not you charge anyone.
Neither Small Team Use nor Non-Production Use overrides them. Doing any of the
following is not licensed.

**No hosted or managed service.** You may not make the software available to
third parties as a hosted or managed service when that service gives its users
access to any substantial set of the software's features or functionality. This
limitation is not about how big you are: it binds a company under the size limit
exactly as it binds a company over it, and it applies whether or not you charge
for the service.

For clarity: running the software for your own company — for its employees and
contractors, and for the work your company does for its own customers — is not
making it available as a hosted or managed service. Offering the software's
functionality to users outside your company, as a product or a service, hosted
by you or on your behalf, is.

**No defeating license enforcement.** You may not move, change, disable, or
circumvent any license key, license check, entitlement check, or other
license-enforcement functionality in the software, and you may not remove,
disable, or obscure any functionality that such a mechanism protects. This
applies to license-enforcement functionality in the software as you receive it
and to any such functionality in later versions. The licensor is under no
obligation to include any license-enforcement functionality, and does not waive
this limitation by leaving it out.

**No stripping notices.** You may not alter, remove, or obscure any licensing,
copyright, authorship, or other notice of the licensor in the software, in its
user interface, or in its documentation.

